#Q 0: What is pneumonia, and what is the point/benefit of being able to identify it from X-rays automatically?

Ans:

Pneumonia is a respiratory infection which causes inflammation in one or both lungs. This is because of fill with fluid or pus. Generally it is caused by bacteria, viruses, or fungi.

Benefits of automatic detection from X-rays:

  • Easy & Early diagnosis

  • Scalability can be increased

  • Consistency

  • Optimization of resources

#Q 2: From looking at only 3 images do you see any attribute of the images that we may have to normalise before training a model?

Yes, some attributes need to be normiased. Sample of 4 chest X-ray images from the dataset, following are some observations:

  • Some scans are overexposed (brighter) than others.

  • Some Artifacts or Medical Devices are seen-Chance of wrong reading.

  • Image are not uniformly Positioned and Framed

  • Label Markings R

    With the above observations, attributes like pixel intensity, Resizing and Brightness to be noramalised.

process_images <- function(shuffled_dataset) {
  
  img_size <- 224  # Desired image size
  
  # Initialize an empty list to store processed images
  X <- list()
  
  # Loop through each image path in shuffled_train_dataset
  for (image_path in shuffled_dataset) {
    # Read the image
    img <- imager::load.image(image_path)
    
    # Normalize the image
    img_normalized <- img / 255
    
    # Resize the image
    img_resized <- resize(img_normalized, img_size, img_size)
    
    # Append the processed image to the list
    X <- c(X, list(img_resized))
  }
  
  return(X)
}
train_X <- process_images(shuffled_train_dataset)
test_X <- process_images(shuffled_test_dataset)

#Q3: If the dataset was not balanced, what kind of techniques could be useful?

In the case of the dataset is not balanced, there are high chances that model could become biased. In order to mitigate or nullify this, techniques like more/under sampling, Data diversity, Giving weightage, Balanced batches during training are to be implemented

# Define a custom dataset class
ImageDataset <- dataset(
  name = "ImageDataset",
  initialize = function(X, y) {
    # Store the data as tensors
    self$data <- torch_tensor(X)
    self$labels <- torch_tensor(y)
  },
  .getitem = function(i) {
    # Return a single sample and label
    x <- self$data[i,,,]
    y <- self$labels[i]
    list(x = x, y = y)
  },
  .length = function() {
    # Return the number of samples
    dim(self$data)[1]
  }
)

# Create a dataset object from your data

net <- nn_module(
  "Net",
  
  initialize = function() {
    self$conv1 <- nn_conv2d(1, 32, 3, 1)
    self$conv2 <- nn_conv2d(32, 64, 3, 1)
    self$dropout1 <- nn_dropout2d(0.25)
    self$dropout2 <- nn_dropout2d(0.5)
    self$fc1 <- nn_linear(774400, 128)  # Adjust the input size based on your image dimensions
    self$fc2 <- nn_linear(128, 2)             # Change the output size to match your classification task
  },
  
  forward = function(x) {
    x %>%                                        # N * 1 * 224 * 224
      self$conv1() %>%                           # N * 32 * 222 * 222
      nnf_relu() %>% 
      self$conv2() %>%                           # N * 64 * 220 * 220
      nnf_relu() %>% 
      nnf_max_pool2d(2) %>%                      # N * 64 * 110 * 110
      self$dropout1() %>% 
      torch_flatten(start_dim = 2) %>%           # N * 64 * 110 * 110 --> N * 774400
      self$fc1() %>%                             # N * 128
      nnf_relu() %>% 
      self$dropout2() %>% 
      self$fc2()                                 # N * 2 (change the output size to match your classification task)
  }
)

Epoch 1: Train Accuracy 48%, Validation Accuracy 50%

Epoch 2: Train Accuracy 51%, Validation Accuracy 50%

Epoch 3: Train Accuracy 49%, Validation Accuracy 50%

With the info, it is clearly evident that the model performs is only accurate upto 50%.

Reasons of less accuracy:

  • Model is lacking to understad complex images

  • Less training data.

  • Less variations in data

# Define a custom dataset class with transformations
ImageDataset_augment <- dataset(
  name = "ImageDataset",
  initialize = function(X, y, transform = NULL) {
    self$transform <- transform
    self$data <- X
    self$labels <- y
  },
  .getitem = function(i) {
    # Return a single sample and label
    x <- self$data[i,,,]
    x <- self$transform(x)
    y <- self$labels[i]
    
    list(x = x, y = y)
  },
  .length = function() {
    dim(self$data)[1]
  }
)

# Define the transformations for training data
train_transforms <- function(img) {
  img <- torch_squeeze(torch_tensor(img)) %>%
    transform_color_jitter() %>%
    transform_random_horizontal_flip() %>%
    transform_random_vertical_flip(p = 0.5) %>%
    torch_unsqueeze(dim = 1)
  
  return(img)
}

# Apply the transformations to your training dataset
train_dataset <- ImageDataset_augment(train_X, train_y, transform = train_transforms)
test_dataset <- ImageDataset(test_X, test_y)
val_dataset <- ImageDataset(val_X, val_y)

# Create a dataloader for training
train_dataloader <- dataloader(train_dataset, batch_size = 16)
test_dataloader <- dataloader(test_dataset, batch_size = 16)
val_dataloader <- dataloader(val_dataset, batch_size = 16)

# Iterate over batches of data
batch = train_dataloader$.iter()$.next()

# Visualize the first batch size
batch[[1]]$size()
## [1]  16   1 224 224

#Q 6: What are the potential drawbacks or disadvantages of data augmentation?

Data augmentation is very powerful technique that can improve the model generalization.

Drawbacks also exisit for data augmentation:

1. Increased Training Time

2. Risk of sorting critical consitions

3. Computational Overhead

Hence, data augmentation need to be applied carefully and contextually.

#Q 7: What is ImageNet aka ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012? How many images and classes does it involve? Why might this help us?

ImageNet is a large-scale visual database designed for use in object recognition research. It became widely known through the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge (ILSVRC), first held in 2010.

In the 2012 competition, deep learning models like AlexNet revolutionized the field by achieving a significant jump in accuracy over traditional methods.

Key Facts about ImageNet (ILSVRC 2012):

  • Over 1.2 million labeled images in the training set
  • 1,000 distinct object categories
  • Images are richly annotated and vary in viewpoint, lighting, and context

General visual features such as: - Edges - Textures - Shapes - Spatial hierarchies, might help the model.

#Q 8: Why do you think using this architecture in this practical assignment can help to improve the results?

MobileNet is a lightweight, efficient CNN architecture designed specifically for devices with limited computing power, such as mobile and embedded devices. Despite being compact, it delivers strong performance for image classification tasks.

Key features of MobileNet:

  • Depthwise separable convolutions
  • Fewer parameters
  • Pretrained on ImageNet

How MobileNet helps in this assignment:

  • Faster training and inference

  • Less prone to overfitting

  • Better generalization

  • Efficient memory usage

  • Good baseline

#Q 10: Using the provided materials in this practical, train a different network architecture. Does this perform better?

I treid training with different architecture ie.. **pretrained MobileNetV2** architecture from the `torchvision` package. But I could not do it successfull, As my system did not support and R is crashing.

To assess whether a different model architecture performs better, I defined a second, simplified convolutional neural network called SimpleCNN_v2. This model used fewer filters (8 and 16), a larger initial kernel size (5x5), and fewer fully connected units compared to the original.

SimpleCNN_v2 <- nn_module(
  initialize = function() {
    self$conv1 <- nn_conv2d(1, 8, kernel_size = 5, padding = 2)
    self$pool <- nn_max_pool2d(kernel_size = 2)
    self$conv2 <- nn_conv2d(8, 16, kernel_size = 3, padding = 1)
    self$fc1 <- nn_linear(16 * 56 * 56, 64)
    self$fc2 <- nn_linear(64, 2)
  },

  forward = function(x) {
    x %>%
      self$conv1() %>%
      nnf_relu() %>%
      self$pool() %>%
      self$conv2() %>%
      nnf_relu() %>%
      self$pool() %>%
      torch_flatten(start_dim = 2) %>%
      self$fc1() %>%
      nnf_relu() %>%
      self$fc2()
  }
)
model_v2 <- SimpleCNN_v2 %>%
  setup(
    loss = nn_cross_entropy_loss(),
    optimizer = optim_adam,
    metrics = list(luz_metric_accuracy())
  ) %>%
  set_hparams() %>%
  set_opt_hparams(lr = 0.001)
fitted_v2 <- model_v2 %>%
  fit(
    train_dataloader,
    epochs = 1,
    valid_data = test_dataloader
  )

While SimpleCNN_v2 is simpler than the original model, but still achieved almost similar performance (~50% accuracy), suggesting that more complex architectures might not always lead to better results- especially with small datasets.
